  "commentaries": {
    "sayana": {
      "rishi": "Atreya",
      "chandas": "Mahāvirāṭ",
      "devata": "Śambhu",
      "sanskrit": "सा० मा० दुन्दुभ्यां भेर्यौ भवः शब्दो दुन्दुभ्यः । आहन्यते ताड्यतेऽनेने-",
      "english": "'Dhrishnuh'—one who does not flee in battle. 'Pramrishah'—one who examines (paramarshaka) the essential reality of the enemy's army. (2)"
    },
    "bhatta_bhaskara": {
      "rishi": "Atreya",
      "chandas": "Mahāvirāṭ",
      "devata": "Śambhu",
      "sanskrit": "",
      "english": "'Namo dhrishnave cha'—to him whose nature is to overpower. Or: to him who is skilled in protecting the entire universe. [Grammatical note]. Even though powerful, he is without partiality towards any particular field—'pramrishaya cha'—to the one skilled in discerning (examining) everything, the wise (pandita). [Grammatical note]. Another says: 'pramrishah' means one of distinguished character. For all indeed worship the God for their own desires, or for well-being, or for supreme liberation; the God, considering that as his own purpose, protects them. (2)"
    },
